  "title": "Concept-based Steering of Large Language Models for Conditional Molecular Generation",
  "experiments_summary": "The paper evaluates CAST (Concept-based Activation STeering) on molecular generation tasks using multiple LLMs (Chemlactica-125M, Chemlactica-1.3B, Chemma-2B, and Qwen3-4B). Experiments are conducted on: (1) In-distribution datasets from Therapeutics Data Commons (ZINC, MOSES, ChemBL) with N=2000 randomly sampled QED and LogP property combinations; (2) Out-of-distribution settings including single property targets, multiple property combinations, and the Conjugated-xTB dataset; (3) Qualitative analysis examining novelty (presence in PubChem database) and synthesizability (SA scores via RDKit). The method involves: extracting hidden representations from a specific intermediate layer of a frozen LLM, passing them through a Concept Bottleneck Model (CBM) that learns property-specific embedding vectors, computing steering vectors as weighted combinations of these embeddings, and adding these vectors to the LLM's hidden activations during generation. The CBM is trained using Normalized Mean Squared Error loss plus an orthogonality loss between embedding vectors, with backpropagation only through the CBM and property MLPs while keeping LLM parameters frozen. Baselines include vanilla LLMs, ActAdd steering, full supervised fine-tuning, and LoRA fine-tuning. Evaluation metrics include Mean Absolute Error (MAE), Best100MAE, validity, generative efficiency (GenEff), uniqueness, novelty, and synthetic accessibility scores. Additional ablation studies examine steering strength variation and its effects on property values and molecular validity."
